<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>izmalis</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Teacher<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Aug 2002<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p>First impression: glad this is being looked at finally.<br />
<br />
Recurring impression: why is it okay for us to heal worse than druids, particularly since our primary ability (slow), has been marginalized by mitigation and fast fights?  That was the #1 reason why we got lesser heals starting at L58 w/ Kraggs: slow acted as indirect healing.  That reason is gone once you get to mobs that mitigate slow regularly and do high dps w/ low hps.  Veeshan_murtak has pointed this out repeatedly- does anyone else even notice?<br />
<br />
I could live w/ our penalties to healing up until now, when I finally reached a level of gear and aa's that my bazaar friends and I could do LDoN hards and go after nameds in Tactics/BoT.  But no longer.  Now if we want to play, I have to camp Iz and load up a friend's cleric.  How lame is that?<br />
<br />
The Daluda heal should instead be a simple change to the existing spell, Tnargs, not a rare new spell that only GoD raid shaman will see.  In addition, since apparently slow mitigation and quick, high dps fights are here to stay, where's our 4k "cheal" at L64 that was there prior to PoP? The reasons for removing it no longer exist- give it back now as a spectral at the very least.<br />
<br />
Can you imagine the screaming from clerics if their healing was mitigated such that it was not noticeably better than any other healer? Or druids if their snares/nukes were mitigated?  Yet here we sit w/ our primary ability, the ability around which we pay so many penalties, reduced in effectiveness and farmed out to many other classes and it's okay.<br />
<br />
3 other classes having nearly as effective slow = okay.  Shaman having a cheal 1/2 as good as clerics = very very bad!<br />
<br />
Pffffffffft.</p>
	
	
	
