<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Grizlor</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	PoWater Guru<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: May 2002<br />
	Location: Rockin' the Lot in my 1996 Jetta
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><b>Tnarg's wasn't designed for content where monsters Mitigated slow</b>. It's an ethereal spell, and was available to anyone in the first 4 planes in POP. It's outdated for elemental/GoD content where slow mitigation runs rampant and further cuts into our ability to counter DPS being done to a tank.<br />
<br />
With two mobs that do identical DPS unslowed, the one that mitigates slow by 50% will deal two and a half times as much damage than the one that doesn't mitigate.<br />
<br />
<font size="3"><b>Two and a half times!!!</b></font> <br />
<br />
Something that is "Mostly" Slowable (Slow is 75% effective) a mob is doing close to <b>twice</b> as much damage as a fully slowable one.<br />
<br />
In content where <b>everything</b> mitigates, We need at least some sort of boost to our healing power to reflect this, and keeping us at a deadset ratio to other healers isn't going to cut it. Throw us a frickin' bone if you're going to limit our ability to prevent damage, or allow us (and only us) to at least somewhat overcome these limitations in a different way.<br />
<br />
Enchanters can still CC, Stun, provide mana regen, haste the group, and nuke decently where stuff is slow immune. A beastlord can still provide monk level DPS, 50% KEI, and paragon, as well as shaman level buffs. As for us, we're dead in the water. This spell is a step in the right direction, now  put the other foot down and actually make it worthwhile.</p>
	
	
	
